track_notes: This route starts on AZ State Trust Land (permit required), then crosses into the National Forest.  The first couple of miles are along dirt road but unless you have a really good 4WD or an ATV you will likely need to hike it.  The last couple of miles are a mix of bushwhack and light trail - the trail comes and goes but definitely helps.  Some sections are steep, plenty of rocks and grasses so gaitors are highly recommended.  Views are really beautiful at the summit and there is a large activation zone - K9PM and myself had no trouble setting up two stations on opposite sides of the summit.  The only wildlife seen were cattle but in warmer months there are probably more critters about.

I did Fagan Mountain on an 80 degree day. It was a bit too hot because there is no shade. I rode my bike into the lake and hiked from there. I found a much better line on the way down. In fact, there was a pretty good trail all the way down from the summit. If you follow my down track, it will keep you on the trail most of the way except near bottom where you leave trail. The trail is hard to follow going up due to the deep grass. Also, on the two steep sections, the trail is vague or not there. 
Good cell coverage on top and a few trees to hold up wire antenna or hide from the sun. Take your long pants, shirt, and full gloves. Lots of prickly bushes that are hard to avoid at times. Also, this hike has a lot more elevation than you think due to a lot of up and down and false summits. I rode my bike from the highway to the lake and hiked from there. GPS said 5.2 miles from highway and 2700 feet if you include the up and down.
